00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:07,360
and an unfertilized oocyte, quiescent.

143
00:10:07,360 --> 00:10:12,280
And then through the process of embryonic development, we became one of these functional

144
00:10:12,280 --> 00:10:15,560
creatures or even something like this.

145
00:10:15,560 --> 00:10:24,960
And the crucial thing about this process of self-construction is that there is no magical

146
00:10:24,960 --> 00:10:30,800
sort of sharp red line at which point you go from being just physics to being a true

147
00:10:30,800 --> 00:10:32,120
cognitive being.

148
00:10:32,120 --> 00:10:36,840
So many people would like to look at themselves and say, we have true, you name it, sentience,

149
00:10:36,840 --> 00:10:40,240
cognition, intelligence, whatever term you want.

150
00:10:40,240 --> 00:10:44,560
And then they would look at something like this, which is a little blob of chemicals.

151
00:10:44,560 --> 00:10:47,040
And they say, well, that certainly doesn't have any of those things.

152
00:10:47,040 --> 00:10:51,280
And so then you owe a story of how you got from here to there.

153
00:10:51,280 --> 00:10:56,360
And that story cannot be any kind of a sharp change.

154
00:10:56,360 --> 00:11:02,160
It has to be a gradual process that is in concert with what we know about embryonic development

155
00:11:02,160 --> 00:11:03,660
and so on.

156
00:11:03,660 --> 00:11:04,660
So that's interesting.

157
00:11:04,660 --> 00:11:09,120
So we go from matter to mind in this way that I think developmental biology is maybe the

158
00:11:09,440 --> 00:11:11,680
most magical of the sciences.

159
00:11:11,680 --> 00:11:14,960
But at least we tend to think of ourselves, once we get here, we tend to think of ourselves

160
00:11:14,960 --> 00:11:19,240
as some sort of a unified intelligence.

161
00:11:19,240 --> 00:11:24,160
And in fact, we often, people will contrast the kinds of thing that we are with something

162
00:11:24,160 --> 00:11:29,760
like ant colonies or bee swarms or something like that and say, well, we talk about that

163
00:11:29,760 --> 00:11:32,640
as a collective intelligence, but that's a metaphor.

164
00:11:32,640 --> 00:11:36,520
We are a true intelligence, collective intelligence is something else.

165
00:11:36,520 --> 00:11:39,680
But actually, this is not the case.

166
00:11:39,680 --> 00:11:43,880
And so Descartes, for example, was really interested in the pineal gland because he said that the

167
00:11:43,880 --> 00:11:50,000
pineal gland was unique, it was an unpaired organ in the brain and therefore a kind of

168
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:54,480
a singular unified location for the mind to interact with the body.

169
00:11:54,480 --> 00:11:58,160
But if he had had access to good microscopy, what he would have discovered is that there

170
00:11:58,160 --> 00:12:00,360
isn't one of anything in the brain.

171
00:12:00,360 --> 00:12:04,120
In fact, inside the pineal gland, you see this, which is a huge number of individual

172
00:12:04,120 --> 00:12:05,440
cells.

173
00:12:06,080 --> 00:12:09,680
If he had had this technology, he could have looked inside of any one of those cells and

174
00:12:09,680 --> 00:12:14,040
discovered that they, in fact, are made of a huge number of different components and

175
00:12:14,040 --> 00:12:15,440
various kinds of active matter.

176
00:12:15,440 --> 00:12:21,520
So there are mitochondria, there are little motors that zip up and down various filaments,

177
00:12:21,520 --> 00:12:23,760
just an incredible number of parts.

178
00:12:23,760 --> 00:12:27,360
And so all of us are collective intelligences.

179
00:12:27,360 --> 00:12:33,240
I'm not aware of any intelligence that is really just some sort of one indivisible diamond

180
00:12:33,240 --> 00:12:34,560
of mind.

181
00:12:34,560 --> 00:12:37,040
We are all made of parts of different kinds.

182
00:12:37,040 --> 00:12:39,600
And so this is the sort of thing we're made of.

183
00:12:39,600 --> 00:12:42,400
This is a single cell, it's called the lacrimaria.

184
00:12:42,400 --> 00:12:45,640
This is a unicellular organism.

185
00:12:45,640 --> 00:12:48,840
It has no brain, it has no nervous system, no stem cells.

186
00:12:48,840 --> 00:12:57,120
It has remarkable competencies over its physiological, metabolic, and anatomical goals.

187
00:12:57,120 --> 00:13:02,920
So you can see here that it's basically, this is at hunting in its environment.

188
00:13:02,920 --> 00:13:06,800
If you're into soft-body robotics, this is an amazing design challenge.

189
00:13:06,800 --> 00:13:10,760
We don't have anything remotely this competent.

190
00:13:10,760 --> 00:13:13,800
And cells have all kinds of other interesting capabilities.

191
00:13:13,800 --> 00:13:17,560
So this is the sort of thing that's studied in the field of diverse intelligence or basal

