00:13:34,080 --> 00:13:35,080
They're completely inert.

201
00:13:35,080 --> 00:13:36,080
They're very thin.

202
00:13:36,080 --> 00:13:38,880
They have no food or any kind of a chemical substance on them.

203
00:13:38,880 --> 00:13:43,880
But what happens is that this, and by the way, this slime mold, it's a single cell.

204
00:13:43,880 --> 00:13:46,200
It can be very large, but the whole thing is a single cell.

205
00:13:46,200 --> 00:13:50,840
So what it starts to do is it starts to grow out, basically in every direction at once.

206
00:13:50,840 --> 00:13:56,000
But during this time, during these 600 minutes or so, what it's actually doing as we discovered

207
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:00,600
is gently tugging on the material around it and reading the strain angle that comes

208
00:14:00,600 --> 00:14:01,600
back.

209
00:14:01,600 --> 00:14:07,120
And based on that strain angle, it builds up towards a decision of where the heavier

210
00:14:07,120 --> 00:14:08,280
mass is.

211
00:14:08,280 --> 00:14:11,720
And the way we know this is because reliably what it's going to do is grow towards the

212
00:14:11,720 --> 00:14:12,960
heavier mass.

213
00:14:12,960 --> 00:14:17,520
And so by reading that strain angle, it's able to gain some knowledge of its environment.

214
00:14:17,520 --> 00:14:22,360
And then for some reason that we don't know, it prefers moving towards the heavier masses.

215
00:14:22,360 --> 00:14:28,800
And so we see that we have this biological material that's very sort of ancient and early

216
00:14:28,800 --> 00:14:32,160
in life has interesting capabilities.

217
00:14:32,160 --> 00:14:37,040
And then the real question becomes, how do these things scale up?

218
00:14:37,040 --> 00:14:41,480
What is it that allows combinations of these cells to do something like this?

