941
00:56:10,840 --> 00:56:14,760
that if we were able to read out these electrical signals,

942
00:56:15,320 --> 00:56:18,600
we could decode them and thus know what the fish is thinking.

943
00:56:18,600 --> 00:56:23,160
We should be able to recover the memories, the goals, the various preferences,

944
00:56:23,160 --> 00:56:26,600
the behavioral repertoires, and so on by decoding this.

945
00:56:26,600 --> 00:56:32,600
So to summarize, and this is the project of neural decoding here in neuroscience,

946
00:56:32,600 --> 00:56:36,440
where you try to image the brain and you make a model

947
00:56:36,440 --> 00:56:39,720
and you understand what that animal is thinking or seeing and so on.

948
00:56:39,720 --> 00:56:45,880
And so the idea is that according to neuroscience,

949
00:56:45,880 --> 00:56:49,080
the bioelectrical signaling in the brain is literally the medium

950
00:56:49,080 --> 00:56:51,800
that contains the cognitive content of the mind.

951
00:56:51,800 --> 00:56:54,520
So you as a person, all your memories and thoughts and everything else

952
00:56:54,520 --> 00:56:58,040
is in some way encoded in the electrophysiology of your brain.

953
00:56:58,040 --> 00:57:00,760
Well, the amazing thing is that this ancient...

954
00:57:00,760 --> 00:57:02,520
So that's a really neat trick, right?

955
00:57:02,520 --> 00:57:05,000
That combination of hardware and software is amazing.

956
00:57:05,800 --> 00:57:09,880
But what's really interesting is that architecture,

957
00:57:09,880 --> 00:57:12,200
the architecture of having this electrical hardware

958
00:57:12,200 --> 00:57:18,680
and thus this very plastic goal seeking clever and problem-solving software

959
00:57:18,680 --> 00:57:20,360
is absolutely ancient.

960
00:57:20,360 --> 00:57:23,160
So every cell in your body has ion channels.

961
00:57:23,160 --> 00:57:27,240
Most of them have gab junctions to neighboring cells.

962
00:57:27,240 --> 00:57:32,520
This is not something that's just for neural cells

963
00:57:32,520 --> 00:57:35,880
and it's something that's been around since the time of bacterial biofilms.

964
00:57:35,880 --> 00:57:39,240
This is evolution figured out this architecture very early on.

965
00:57:39,240 --> 00:57:44,520
And so then one can try to extend this and basically this is the project

966
00:57:44,520 --> 00:57:47,560
and this is what we've been doing for almost 30 years now

967
00:57:47,560 --> 00:57:51,720
is this idea of extending neuroscience beyond neurons.

968
00:57:51,720 --> 00:57:56,680
The real kind of magic of neuroscience is not in the neurons.

969
00:57:56,680 --> 00:58:00,440
It's in this understanding, this scaling up of cognition.

970
00:58:00,440 --> 00:58:05,560
And so what you might imagine is doing exactly the same kind of neural decoding thing,

971
00:58:05,560 --> 00:58:06,520
but not on neurons.

972
00:58:06,520 --> 00:58:09,560
Let's say on embryos or some other morphogenetic system to ask,

973
00:58:10,280 --> 00:58:13,400
here you're asking what is the collective intelligence of neurons thinking.

974
00:58:13,960 --> 00:58:16,600
Here you're asking for what is the collective intelligence

975
00:58:16,600 --> 00:58:20,760
of the rest of the body cells thinking quite literally.

976
00:58:21,560 --> 00:58:24,760
And I can use the thing is, this sounds very strange

977
00:58:24,760 --> 00:58:28,680
and a lot of people will say that this is some kind of a weird misuse of a metaphor.

978
00:58:28,680 --> 00:58:32,440
But the reason that I can apply all this terminology from neuroscience

979
00:58:32,520 --> 00:58:38,600
to outside the brain is because the concepts, the tools, the reagents

980
00:58:38,600 --> 00:58:42,600
cannot tell the difference between neurons and non-neural tissues.

981
00:58:42,600 --> 00:58:45,480
All of the same tools and concepts work everywhere in the body.

982
00:58:45,480 --> 00:58:46,760
This is what we've been showing.

983
00:58:46,760 --> 00:58:50,360
And so the concepts are actually very isomorphic.

984
00:58:50,360 --> 00:58:56,040
And so what you have here is that whereas the electrical network,

985
00:58:56,040 --> 00:58:57,880
just to kind of summarize what I'm saying here,

986
00:58:58,440 --> 00:59:03,320
the electrical network of the brain is giving commands to the muscles

987
00:59:03,320 --> 00:59:05,800
to move you through three dimensional space.

988
00:59:05,800 --> 00:59:08,520
That's the familiar version of neuroscience.

989
00:59:08,520 --> 00:59:10,840
And then we can modify it with various techniques

990
00:59:10,840 --> 00:59:12,520
and we can read it out and so on.

991
00:59:12,520 --> 00:59:15,720
So the electrical network of the brain tells muscles what to do

992
00:59:15,720 --> 00:59:17,800
to move you in three dimensional space.

993
00:59:17,800 --> 00:59:19,880
But the reason it can do that is because it evolved

994
00:59:19,880 --> 00:59:23,560
from a much more ancient system in other tissues in your body

995
00:59:23,640 --> 00:59:26,440
that long before brains and muscles evolved,

996
00:59:26,440 --> 00:59:32,120
we're telling all the cells how to rearrange your body shape

997
00:59:32,120 --> 00:59:35,400
and thus move you in anatomical morphospace.

998
00:59:35,400 --> 00:59:39,640
Same strategy, same hardware, same tricks, except it's a different space.

999
00:59:39,640 --> 00:59:42,360
And so this is what I said before when I said that evolution

1000
00:59:42,360 --> 00:59:45,000
was pivoting us through various problem spaces.

1001
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:49,480
So what we did was to develop the first molecular tools

1002
00:59:49,480 --> 00:59:53,160
to read and write this information outside of the nervous system.

1003
00:59:53,160 --> 00:59:54,440
So how do we do that?

1004
00:59:54,440 --> 00:59:59,160
So the first thing is a voltage sensitive fluorescent dye.

1005
00:59:59,160 --> 01:00:03,320
So this is a chemical that emits either different brightness

1006
01:00:03,320 --> 01:00:07,080
or different wavelengths, light depending on the electrical properties

1007
01:00:07,080 --> 01:00:08,440
of the cell that it's sitting in.

1008
01:00:08,440 --> 01:00:13,400
And so what you're seeing here is a time lapse of a frog embryo

1009
01:00:13,400 --> 01:00:15,160
as during the early stages.

1010
01:00:15,160 --> 01:00:19,000
And so the colors represent different voltages.

1011
01:00:19,000 --> 01:00:23,720
And so this is a kind of brain scan, if you will,

1012
01:00:24,440 --> 01:00:27,400
of all the conversations that the cells are having with each other

1013
01:00:27,400 --> 01:00:30,120
as they sort out who's going to be left, who's going to be right,

1014
01:00:30,120 --> 01:00:33,240
who's going to be anterior, posterior, dorsal, ventral, and so on.

1015
01:00:33,240 --> 01:00:39,800
And so we now have the ability to read out this kind of information.

1016
01:00:39,800 --> 01:00:42,440
We spend a lot of time doing computer simulations

1017
01:00:42,440 --> 01:00:46,440
to figure out how these patterns map onto the patterns of ion channels

1018
01:00:46,440 --> 01:00:48,200
that are present in the cell membranes.

1019
01:00:48,200 --> 01:00:49,720
I want to show you two kinds of patterns.

1020
01:00:50,440 --> 01:00:52,360
The first we call the electric face.

1021
01:00:52,360 --> 01:00:53,800
And this is, again, a time lapse.

1022
01:00:53,800 --> 01:00:56,760
Now here, it's gray scale instead of color, but it's the same idea.

1023
01:00:56,760 --> 01:00:59,160
The brightness represents voltage.

1024
01:00:59,160 --> 01:01:02,440
And so in this early frog embryo that's putting its face together,

1025
01:01:02,440 --> 01:01:04,920
there's all kinds of changes, lots of exciting stuff happening.

1026
01:01:04,920 --> 01:01:06,920
But look at this one frame taken from it.

1027
01:01:08,120 --> 01:01:11,960
Long before the genes are turned on to make the different parts of the face,

1028
01:01:11,960 --> 01:01:14,360
we can already see what this animal is going to do.

1029
01:01:14,360 --> 01:01:16,200
Here's where the animal's right eye is going to be.

1030
01:01:16,200 --> 01:01:17,720
Here's where the mouth is going to be.

1031
01:01:17,720 --> 01:01:19,720
The left eye comes in slightly thereafter.

1032
01:01:19,720 --> 01:01:21,160
You will see that momentarily.

1033
01:01:22,680 --> 01:01:25,160
Here are the placodes on the sides.

1034
01:01:25,160 --> 01:01:29,080
The B pattern of where everything is going to go

1035
01:01:29,080 --> 01:01:34,840
is already there in the stable electrical states of the cells

1036
01:01:34,840 --> 01:01:36,440
if you know how to read them out.

1037
01:01:36,440 --> 01:01:37,880
So this is the electric face.

1038
01:01:37,880 --> 01:01:42,520
And I'm going to show you in a minute that if you make changes here,

1039
01:01:42,520 --> 01:01:43,880
you will change gene expression.

1040
01:01:43,880 --> 01:01:44,920
You will change anatomy.

1041
01:01:44,920 --> 01:01:47,240
Therefore, this pattern is instructive.

1042
01:01:47,320 --> 01:01:47,960
It drives.

1043
01:01:47,960 --> 01:01:49,960
This is not just some sort of epiphenomenon.

1044
01:01:49,960 --> 01:01:55,080
This is actually the memory of what the cells are going to be doing

1045
01:01:55,800 --> 01:01:56,600
to make the face.

1046
01:01:56,600 --> 01:01:58,040
So that's a natural pattern.

1047
01:01:58,040 --> 01:02:01,480
But here's a pathological pattern.

1048
01:02:01,480 --> 01:02:04,040
And we'll talk more about cancer in the third part of the talk.

1049
01:02:04,040 --> 01:02:08,440
If I inject a human oncogene, there will be a tumor.

1050
01:02:10,040 --> 01:02:11,720
But before that tumor forms,

1051
01:02:11,720 --> 01:02:19,080
I can already see where the cells are starting to defect.

1052
01:02:19,080 --> 01:02:21,240
They acquire this abnormal bioelectric state.

1053
01:02:21,880 --> 01:02:23,640
And I can already see where the tumor is going to be.

1054
01:02:23,640 --> 01:02:25,240
So this is a pathological pattern.

1055
01:02:25,240 --> 01:02:27,560
So in addition to being able to observe all this stuff,

1056
01:02:27,560 --> 01:02:30,120
which is nice, but it's just observation,

1057
01:02:31,320 --> 01:02:34,600
what we developed were a set of tools patterned on exactly the same thing

1058
01:02:34,600 --> 01:02:38,200
done in neuroscience to study synaptic plasticity and intrinsic plasticity.

1059
01:02:38,760 --> 01:02:43,400
And basically be able to, so I showed you how to read the patterns.

1060
01:02:43,400 --> 01:02:44,920
I'm showing you how to write the patterns.

1061
01:02:44,920 --> 01:02:48,840
So you can rewrite those patterns by manipulating the gap junctions,

1062
01:02:48,840 --> 01:02:50,200
these electrical synapses.

1063
01:02:50,200 --> 01:02:53,000
So that controls the connectivity of this network.

1064
01:02:53,000 --> 01:02:55,880
Or you can actually open channels, open them,

1065
01:02:56,920 --> 01:02:59,240
using drugs or close them using drugs, using light,

1066
01:02:59,240 --> 01:03:03,320
the various kinds of stimuli to control the voltage of every cell.

1067
01:03:03,320 --> 01:03:06,200
So to be clear, there are no applied fields.

1068
01:03:06,200 --> 01:03:07,400
There are no electrodes.

1069
01:03:07,400 --> 01:03:09,480
There's no electromagnetic radiation.

1070
01:03:09,480 --> 01:03:11,160
There are no magnets, nothing like that.

1071
01:03:11,160 --> 01:03:16,520
This is molecular physiology using the natural interface

1072
01:03:16,520 --> 01:03:18,280
that these cells are exposing to us.

1073
01:03:18,280 --> 01:03:21,560
These, this is the same interface that they use to hack each other.

1074
01:03:21,560 --> 01:03:23,720
These are, this is the way the cells are communicating,

1075
01:03:23,720 --> 01:03:25,000
and we're just hijacking it.

1076
01:03:25,000 --> 01:03:27,400
So there are no external fields, nothing like that.

1077
01:03:28,680 --> 01:03:32,680
Okay, so using this technology then, we know what happens

1078
01:03:32,680 --> 01:03:33,640
when you use it in the brain.

1079
01:03:33,640 --> 01:03:35,960
So somebody like Tanagawa at MIT can use this

1080
01:03:35,960 --> 01:03:39,240
to put false memories into the brains of mice,

1081
01:03:39,240 --> 01:03:41,560
using exactly this technology in the brain.

1082
01:03:41,560 --> 01:03:43,720
We are going to put false memories

1083
01:03:43,720 --> 01:03:47,240
into the somatic networks of cells that are building the body.

1084
01:03:47,240 --> 01:03:49,000
So when you do that, here's what happens.

1085
01:03:49,640 --> 01:03:54,280
You can convince cells to make ectopic hearts like this.

1086
01:03:54,280 --> 01:03:56,120
Here are some extra hearts in the tadpole.

1087
01:03:56,120 --> 01:03:57,400
You can make extra limbs.

1088
01:03:57,400 --> 01:04:00,200
So you can ask the cells in the jaw to start generating a limb.

1089
01:04:00,200 --> 01:04:03,480
And here are some six-legged frogs here.

1090
01:04:03,480 --> 01:04:05,240
You can make ectopic forebrain.

1091
01:04:05,240 --> 01:04:08,200
You can make ectopic inner ear organs right here.

1092
01:04:08,200 --> 01:04:09,480
Or you can even make fins.

1093
01:04:09,480 --> 01:04:10,680
Now that's especially weird

1094
01:04:10,680 --> 01:04:12,360
because tadpoles aren't supposed to have fins.

1095
01:04:12,360 --> 01:04:14,920
And I'll show you some of that momentarily.

1096
01:04:14,920 --> 01:04:16,760
But here's one of my favorite examples.

1097
01:04:17,640 --> 01:04:19,480
I showed you, if you remember that electric face,

1098
01:04:19,480 --> 01:04:20,920
one of the things about that electric face

1099
01:04:20,920 --> 01:04:24,200
was that there was a pattern that said where the eye should go.

1100
01:04:24,200 --> 01:04:27,000
It represented the location where the cells should become an eye.

1101
01:04:27,080 --> 01:04:30,200
And so we simply said, okay, if we try to reproduce

1102
01:04:30,200 --> 01:04:31,960
that electrical state elsewhere in the body,

1103
01:04:31,960 --> 01:04:35,480
can we induce some other kinds of cells to be an eye?

1104
01:04:37,240 --> 01:04:37,800
And so we did.

1105
01:04:37,800 --> 01:04:40,360
So we injected some mRNA encoding,

1106
01:04:40,360 --> 01:04:44,920
some potassium channels into a different type of cells

1107
01:04:44,920 --> 01:04:47,400
that were not going to be that region.

1108
01:04:47,400 --> 01:04:48,840
In particular, they were this gut.

1109
01:04:48,840 --> 01:04:50,200
They were fated to be gut.

1110
01:04:50,200 --> 01:04:53,560
And if you do that, if you create that pattern in those cells,

1111
01:04:53,560 --> 01:04:55,960
sure enough, they will make, they will build an eye.

1112
01:04:55,960 --> 01:04:58,920
And these eyes will have all the right cell layers.

1113
01:04:58,920 --> 01:05:02,920
So retinal lens, optic nerve, they'll have all that stuff.

1114
01:05:02,920 --> 01:05:04,600
Notice, notice a couple of interesting things.

1115
01:05:04,600 --> 01:05:08,520
Number one, this bioelectric pattern is instructive.

1116
01:05:08,520 --> 01:05:09,720
It tells cells what to do.

1117
01:05:09,720 --> 01:05:11,480
It doesn't just ruin the old pattern,

1118
01:05:11,480 --> 01:05:13,720
it actually can call up whole organs.

1119
01:05:13,720 --> 01:05:17,800
Number two, it expands the notion of competency.

1120
01:05:17,800 --> 01:05:19,720
In the developmental biology textbook,

1121
01:05:19,720 --> 01:05:22,920
what you will read is that only these cells up here

1122
01:05:22,920 --> 01:05:24,360
in the anterior and directed room

1123
01:05:24,360 --> 01:05:26,280
are actually competent to become eye.

1124
01:05:26,280 --> 01:05:29,080
And that's true if you use the traditional way of inducing eyes,

1125
01:05:29,080 --> 01:05:31,240
which is this master eye gene called PAC-6.

1126
01:05:31,240 --> 01:05:33,480
But it's not true if you go up a level

1127
01:05:33,480 --> 01:05:36,440
and use the bioelectric signals, you can make eyes anywhere.

1128
01:05:36,440 --> 01:05:38,280
So it completely changes our idea.

1129
01:05:39,000 --> 01:05:41,160
Learning to hack these cells in a different way

1130
01:05:41,160 --> 01:05:44,600
changes this, our understanding of their competency.

1131
01:05:45,960 --> 01:05:48,440
And notice the third thing that's amazing

1132
01:05:48,440 --> 01:05:51,560
is that we didn't provide very much information at all.

1133
01:05:51,560 --> 01:05:52,760
I mean, eyes are very complex.

1134
01:05:52,840 --> 01:05:55,080
We didn't tell this animal how to make an eye.

1135
01:05:55,080 --> 01:05:59,720
We basically just triggered the eye morphogenetic subroutine

1136
01:05:59,720 --> 01:06:02,280
with a simple trigger that says build an eye here.

1137
01:06:02,280 --> 01:06:02,680
That's it.

1138
01:06:02,680 --> 01:06:04,200
We didn't say where the stem cells go

1139
01:06:04,200 --> 01:06:06,120
or how to make a retina, none of that.

1140
01:06:06,120 --> 01:06:07,240
It's very modular.

1141
01:06:07,240 --> 01:06:08,840
It's very hierarchical.

1142
01:06:09,960 --> 01:06:13,960
And so the next kind of part of this

1143
01:06:13,960 --> 01:06:15,480
that's my favorite is this.

1144
01:06:15,480 --> 01:06:18,440
Here's a lens, an ectopic lens sitting out

1145
01:06:18,440 --> 01:06:20,040
in the tail of a tadpole somewhere.

1146
01:06:20,040 --> 01:06:21,800
So we've induced the lens.

1147
01:06:21,800 --> 01:06:23,320
The way we've induced it is just like here.

1148
01:06:23,320 --> 01:06:25,080
We injected some ion channels.

1149
01:06:25,080 --> 01:06:28,760
These ion channels are labeled with this blue beta-gal signal.

1150
01:06:29,720 --> 01:06:32,200
So what you can see here is that the blue cells are the ones

1151
01:06:32,200 --> 01:06:34,120
to which we said build an eye.

1152
01:06:35,160 --> 01:06:37,800
But there's not enough of them to build a proper lens.

1153
01:06:37,800 --> 01:06:38,600
And so what did they do?

1154
01:06:38,600 --> 01:06:41,080
They recruited a bunch of their nearby buddies,

1155
01:06:41,080 --> 01:06:43,560
all of this stuff here that we never touched.

1156
01:06:44,360 --> 01:06:45,880
So it's a secondary instruction.

1157
01:06:45,880 --> 01:06:48,040
We instruct these cells to make an eye.

1158
01:06:48,040 --> 01:06:50,040
They instruct their neighbors to work with them

1159
01:06:50,040 --> 01:06:51,240
to complete the task.

1160
01:06:51,240 --> 01:06:53,560
This is something you see in other collective intelligence

1161
01:06:53,560 --> 01:06:56,760
is like ants, where when a few ants come across a project

1162
01:06:56,760 --> 01:06:58,520
that's too big for them to handle, what do they do?

1163
01:06:58,520 --> 01:06:59,960
They recruit others.

1164
01:06:59,960 --> 01:07:03,400
And so this ability of the system to self-scale

1165
01:07:03,400 --> 01:07:05,400
to the available problem is something

1166
01:07:05,400 --> 01:07:07,080
that you see in other collective intelligences.

1167
01:07:07,080 --> 01:07:10,760
So we don't have to tell these cells how big an eye should be

1168
01:07:10,760 --> 01:07:12,360
or how many cells there should be.

1169
01:07:12,360 --> 01:07:14,120
All of this is part of the competency

1170
01:07:14,120 --> 01:07:17,480
of this amazing agential medium in which we're working.

1171
01:07:17,480 --> 01:07:19,160
And we'll get to that notion.

1172
01:07:19,160 --> 01:07:21,720
But the fact that these cells are solving problems collectively,

1173
01:07:21,720 --> 01:07:24,040
they know how big this group is.

1174
01:07:24,040 --> 01:07:25,480
They know how big it's supposed to be.

1175
01:07:25,480 --> 01:07:28,040
The collective functionally knows all these things

1176
01:07:28,040 --> 01:07:30,760
because you can see it.

1177
01:07:30,760 --> 01:07:35,720
So we use the same kind of strategy

1178
01:07:35,720 --> 01:07:38,280
to address the issue of leg regeneration.

1179
01:07:38,280 --> 01:07:40,760
So frogs normally do not regenerate their legs,

1180
01:07:40,760 --> 01:07:41,960
unlike salamanders.

1181
01:07:41,960 --> 01:07:43,880
But what we can do is after amputation,

1182
01:07:43,880 --> 01:07:46,840
we can treat with a cocktail of ion channel drugs.

1183
01:07:46,840 --> 01:07:49,240
And in fact, they turn on immediately

1184
01:07:49,240 --> 01:07:51,000
these pro regenerative genes.

1185
01:07:51,000 --> 01:07:52,040
They begin to make a leg.

1186
01:07:52,040 --> 01:07:52,920
You've got some toes.

1187
01:07:52,920 --> 01:07:55,640
By 45 days, you've already got a toenail and some toes.

1188
01:07:55,640 --> 01:07:57,560
Eventually, a very nice leg.

1189
01:07:57,560 --> 01:07:59,960
The leg is touch sensitive and motile.

1190
01:07:59,960 --> 01:08:03,880
And all of this happens from a brief modulation.

1191
01:08:03,880 --> 01:08:06,120
In fact, in the recent work on adult frogs,

1192
01:08:06,120 --> 01:08:09,240
we show that just one day, 24 hours of application

1193
01:08:09,240 --> 01:08:13,560
of our cocktail, you get a year and a half of leg growth.

1194
01:08:13,560 --> 01:08:14,920
So this is not 3D printing.

1195
01:08:14,920 --> 01:08:15,960
This is not scaffolds.

1196
01:08:15,960 --> 01:08:17,880
This is not us telling stem cells where to go

1197
01:08:17,880 --> 01:08:19,640
or what tissues go next to what tissues.

1198
01:08:19,640 --> 01:08:21,560
We have no idea how to build a frog leg.

1199
01:08:21,560 --> 01:08:24,040
It'll be a really long time before anybody

1200
01:08:24,040 --> 01:08:26,520
can micromanage that process, but you don't need to.

1201
01:08:26,520 --> 01:08:28,360
Because the cells already know how to do it.

1202
01:08:28,360 --> 01:08:29,880
What you do need to do is to convince them

1203
01:08:29,880 --> 01:08:31,880
that that's what they should do instead of scarring.

1204
01:08:31,880 --> 01:08:33,720
And that doesn't take very long.

1205
01:08:33,720 --> 01:08:35,320
24 hours is plenty.

1206
01:08:35,320 --> 01:08:36,760
And once they've decided that that's

1207
01:08:36,760 --> 01:08:38,680
where they're going in morphogenetic space,

1208
01:08:38,680 --> 01:08:39,880
they will keep going.

1209
01:08:39,880 --> 01:08:41,960
And this is how regenerative medicine

1210
01:08:41,960 --> 01:08:44,840
can take advantage of the competencies of these cells.

1211
01:08:44,920 --> 01:08:46,520
And here I should do a disclosure,

1212
01:08:46,520 --> 01:08:49,160
because David Kaplan and I are co-founders of a company

1213
01:08:49,160 --> 01:08:50,840
called Morphosuticals Inc.

1214
01:08:50,840 --> 01:08:53,000
And what we're trying to do is the same thing in rodents.

1215
01:08:53,000 --> 01:08:55,720
So David makes these amazing wearable bioreactors

1216
01:08:55,720 --> 01:08:59,160
that apply to the wound site, our drug payloads,

1217
01:08:59,160 --> 01:09:01,240
which are various things that attempt

1218
01:09:01,240 --> 01:09:03,720
to convince the cells that they should regenerate.

1219
01:09:03,720 --> 01:09:07,720
So hopefully, eventually, we'll be using this

1220
01:09:07,720 --> 01:09:08,840
in clinical practice.

1221
01:09:08,840 --> 01:09:11,400
For now, we've done it in frog.

1222
01:09:11,400 --> 01:09:14,120
We're currently trying to do it in mammals

1223
01:09:14,120 --> 01:09:16,760
and eventually, hopefully, in patients.

1224
01:09:16,760 --> 01:09:17,720
OK.

1225
01:09:17,720 --> 01:09:21,320
For the next story, I want to switch back to planarium.

1226
01:09:21,320 --> 01:09:23,480
So this kind of animal.

1227
01:09:23,480 --> 01:09:26,440
And I want to, at this point, make good on the promise

1228
01:09:26,440 --> 01:09:28,360
that I made about 10 minutes ago, which

1229
01:09:28,360 --> 01:09:32,040
is to show you how those gold states are actually encoded.

1230
01:09:32,040 --> 01:09:35,400
How does the tissue remember what a correct animal

1231
01:09:35,400 --> 01:09:36,280
should look like?

1232
01:09:36,280 --> 01:09:39,400
And the planaria are a great example of this,

1233
01:09:39,400 --> 01:09:41,800
because if you cut them into pieces,

1234
01:09:41,800 --> 01:09:45,960
and the record is something like 276, I believe,

1235
01:09:45,960 --> 01:09:48,520
each of these pieces regrows a perfect little worm.

1236
01:09:48,520 --> 01:09:51,080
They make exactly what's needed, no more, no less.

1237
01:09:51,080 --> 01:09:53,320
And in fact, it's a tough problem, because even

1238
01:09:53,320 --> 01:09:57,080
if you make just one cut here, these cells back here

1239
01:09:57,080 --> 01:09:58,360
have to make a tail.

1240
01:09:58,360 --> 01:10:00,200
These cells up here have to make a head,

1241
01:10:00,200 --> 01:10:01,720
but they were exact neighbors.

1242
01:10:01,720 --> 01:10:03,080
Right up until the time you cut them,

1243
01:10:03,080 --> 01:10:04,120
they were exact neighbors.

1244
01:10:04,120 --> 01:10:07,320
And yet they have radically different anatomical fates.

1245
01:10:07,320 --> 01:10:08,840
So you cannot decide if you're going

1246
01:10:08,840 --> 01:10:11,080
to be a head or a tail based on your position in the animal.

1247
01:10:11,080 --> 01:10:12,040
They have the same position.

1248
01:10:12,040 --> 01:10:13,160
You can cut anywhere.

1249
01:10:13,160 --> 01:10:15,800
It's after the cut, you have to now figure out,

1250
01:10:15,800 --> 01:10:16,520
what am I missing?

1251
01:10:16,520 --> 01:10:17,480
What do I still have?

1252
01:10:17,480 --> 01:10:20,200
And what does a correct planarian look like?

1253
01:10:20,200 --> 01:10:22,600
So oh, and by the way, these animals are also immoral.

1254
01:10:22,600 --> 01:10:24,800
In case you're interested in aging,

1255
01:10:24,800 --> 01:10:27,080
planaria are, they do not age.

1256
01:10:27,080 --> 01:10:28,600
There's no such thing as an old planarian,

1257
01:10:28,600 --> 01:10:32,120
because they continuously regenerate their tissues.

1258
01:10:32,120 --> 01:10:34,520
So we wanted to ask this simple question.

1259
01:10:34,520 --> 01:10:37,000
OK, here's our planarian.

1260
01:10:37,000 --> 01:10:39,200
And we amputate the head, and we amputate the tail.

1261
01:10:39,240 --> 01:10:41,200
So you have this middle fragment.

1262
01:10:41,200 --> 01:10:43,440
The middle fragment reliably regenerates

1263
01:10:43,440 --> 01:10:45,720
to have one head, one tail.

1264
01:10:45,720 --> 01:10:47,960
How does this piece know how many heads and tails

1265
01:10:47,960 --> 01:10:49,040
it's supposed to have?

1266
01:10:49,040 --> 01:10:52,480
So we investigated and found out that there's actually

1267
01:10:52,480 --> 01:10:54,720
an electrical circuit, which I don't have time to go into,

1268
01:10:54,720 --> 01:10:57,360
but there's an electrical circuit, which actually

1269
01:10:57,360 --> 01:10:59,520
encodes the number of heads that they're supposed to have.

1270
01:10:59,520 --> 01:11:03,760
And so what we were able to do then is this.

1271
01:11:03,760 --> 01:11:08,160
Here is a visualization of the normal electrical pattern

1272
01:11:08,160 --> 01:11:11,040
in these fragments, so one head, one tail.

1273
01:11:11,040 --> 01:11:13,720
But what you can do is you can rewrite that pattern

1274
01:11:13,720 --> 01:11:15,200
to say two heads.

1275
01:11:15,200 --> 01:11:16,920
Now, this is kind of messy still.

1276
01:11:16,920 --> 01:11:19,280
So the technology is still very much in development,

1277
01:11:19,280 --> 01:11:21,480
but you can already see, you can do that.

1278
01:11:21,480 --> 01:11:23,680
And when you do that to this animal,

1279
01:11:23,680 --> 01:11:26,120
they go ahead and they make a two-headed flatworm.

1280
01:11:26,120 --> 01:11:27,000
This is not Photoshop.

1281
01:11:27,000 --> 01:11:29,680
These are real two-headed animals.

1282
01:11:29,680 --> 01:11:31,840
Notice something interesting.

1283
01:11:31,840 --> 01:11:35,120
So here's anatomically one head, one tail.

1284
01:11:35,120 --> 01:11:36,920
The gene expression for the head is, of course,

1285
01:11:36,960 --> 01:11:38,800
in the head and so on.

1286
01:11:38,800 --> 01:11:42,200
This animal, this bioelectrical map

1287
01:11:42,200 --> 01:11:43,760
is not a map of this two-headed guy.

1288
01:11:43,760 --> 01:11:47,480
This is a map of this perfectly normal, anatomically normal,

1289
01:11:47,480 --> 01:11:48,680
one-headed animal.

1290
01:11:48,680 --> 01:11:50,640
Not only is his anatomy still normal,

1291
01:11:50,640 --> 01:11:53,480
his molecular biology is still normal.

1292
01:11:53,480 --> 01:11:56,760
The anterior marker is still only on in the head,

1293
01:11:56,760 --> 01:11:58,280
not in the tail.

1294
01:11:58,280 --> 01:12:01,200
So, and yet, if you were to cut them,

1295
01:12:01,200 --> 01:12:03,280
they go on and to make two-headed flatworms.

1296
01:12:03,320 --> 01:12:06,920
So let me pause here and just explain,

1297
01:12:06,920 --> 01:12:08,680
to underline what's going on here.

1298
01:12:09,680 --> 01:12:12,840
This bioelectrical pattern is what I promised before

1299
01:12:12,840 --> 01:12:16,920
as a readout of where the information

1300
01:12:16,920 --> 01:12:18,480
for the target morphology,

1301
01:12:18,480 --> 01:12:21,080
the target, the correct pattern to build,

1302
01:12:21,080 --> 01:12:22,280
this is where it's stored.

1303
01:12:22,280 --> 01:12:25,200
It is literally stored in this electrical map,

1304
01:12:25,200 --> 01:12:27,640
the way that memories are thought to be stored

1305
01:12:27,640 --> 01:12:28,960
in the brain.

1306
01:12:28,960 --> 01:12:32,480
Also, a single normal planarian body

1307
01:12:32,480 --> 01:12:36,120
is able to store one of two different ideas

1308
01:12:36,120 --> 01:12:38,640
about what a correct planarian should look like.

1309
01:12:38,640 --> 01:12:39,520
In other words, this again,

1310
01:12:39,520 --> 01:12:41,000
sounds very much like the nervous system

1311
01:12:41,000 --> 01:12:43,160
where the exact same hardware, your brain,

1312
01:12:43,160 --> 01:12:46,360
can store many, many different types of ideas,

1313
01:12:46,360 --> 01:12:48,160
and you do not have to genetically edit your brain

1314
01:12:48,160 --> 01:12:51,000
to have it store different types of information.

1315
01:12:51,000 --> 01:12:53,600
It's just built to have different targets

1316
01:12:53,600 --> 01:12:55,600
that it can remember.

1317
01:12:55,600 --> 01:12:58,800
And so, and the third amazing thing about this is that

1318
01:12:58,800 --> 01:13:01,920
this pattern memory is a kind of counterfactual,

1319
01:13:01,920 --> 01:13:05,880
meaning that this is a memory of what I am going to do

1320
01:13:05,880 --> 01:13:07,880
if I get injured in the future.

1321
01:13:07,880 --> 01:13:09,080
It's not what I'm doing now.

1322
01:13:09,080 --> 01:13:11,480
It's what I will do if at some point in the future

1323
01:13:11,480 --> 01:13:12,360
I get injured.

1324
01:13:12,360 --> 01:13:16,080
So that ability to, it's a very primitive version

1325
01:13:16,080 --> 01:13:18,040
of what's sort of magical about brains,

1326
01:13:18,040 --> 01:13:20,680
which is this ability to mental time travel,

1327
01:13:20,680 --> 01:13:23,720
to think about, to have memories of things

1328
01:13:23,720 --> 01:13:25,880
that happened long ago and are not true now,

1329
01:13:25,880 --> 01:13:27,360
and to have anticipation of things

1330
01:13:27,360 --> 01:13:28,440
that might happen in the future

1331
01:13:28,440 --> 01:13:29,920
that are also not happening now.

1332
01:13:29,920 --> 01:13:32,080
People think that this is very much

1333
01:13:32,080 --> 01:13:33,880
the kind of thing that brains do and it is,

1334
01:13:33,880 --> 01:13:37,200
but the evolutionary precursors of that are ancient,

1335
01:13:37,200 --> 01:13:40,560
and even the planarian morphological intelligence

1336
01:13:40,560 --> 01:13:44,560
has a degree of ability to do this kind of mental time travel.

1337
01:13:44,560 --> 01:13:46,440
Now, why do I keep calling it a memory?

1338
01:13:46,440 --> 01:13:50,940
Because if you take these two-headed worms,

1339
01:13:52,320 --> 01:13:53,880
and you cut them again in plain water,

1340
01:13:53,880 --> 01:13:56,800
no more manipulation of any kind,

1341
01:13:56,800 --> 01:13:59,400
they continue to form two-headed animals.

1342
01:13:59,440 --> 01:14:01,600
So no genetic change.

1343
01:14:01,600 --> 01:14:02,680
The hardware is untouched.

1344
01:14:02,680 --> 01:14:04,800
These, the genomes here are exactly the same.

1345
01:14:04,800 --> 01:14:06,160
We haven't done any genomic editing,

1346
01:14:06,160 --> 01:14:07,800
nothing wrong with their genomes.

1347
01:14:07,800 --> 01:14:10,560
And yet this is a permanent line of animals

1348
01:14:10,560 --> 01:14:14,640
that will continue to generate two-headed creatures,

1349
01:14:14,640 --> 01:14:17,240
even though they have the normal wild-type genome.

1350
01:14:17,240 --> 01:14:20,440
So the question of where is,

1351
01:14:20,440 --> 01:14:22,200
remember that slide I showed at the beginning,

1352
01:14:22,200 --> 01:14:23,960
that human torso, and I asked,

1353
01:14:23,960 --> 01:14:25,560
where is that information stored?

1354
01:14:26,640 --> 01:14:28,200
Where is the information stored

1355
01:14:28,200 --> 01:14:30,840
for the number of heads a worm should have?

1356
01:14:30,840 --> 01:14:31,760
It isn't genetic,

1357
01:14:31,760 --> 01:14:34,840
because you can take the exact same genetic hardware

1358
01:14:34,840 --> 01:14:36,760
and have it be two-headed.

1359
01:14:36,760 --> 01:14:38,480
But what the genome does do

1360
01:14:38,480 --> 01:14:41,080
is to build an electrical circuit

1361
01:14:41,080 --> 01:14:44,480
that by default stores the information for one head,

1362
01:14:44,480 --> 01:14:46,320
but it can be pushed to other fates,

1363
01:14:46,320 --> 01:14:48,960
for example, to store information for two heads.

1364
01:14:48,960 --> 01:14:50,120
So this is why I call it memory.

1365
01:14:50,120 --> 01:14:51,800
It's long-term stable.

1366
01:14:51,800 --> 01:14:53,720
It's rewritable, and we can also, by the way,

1367
01:14:53,720 --> 01:14:56,480
take two-headed and put them back to one-headed.

1368
01:14:56,480 --> 01:14:57,640
And it has this latency,

1369
01:14:57,640 --> 01:14:59,360
which I just showed you, this conditional recall.

1370
01:14:59,360 --> 01:15:02,600
It doesn't kick in until you've injured the animal.

1371
01:15:02,600 --> 01:15:03,440
And so here you can see,

1372
01:15:03,440 --> 01:15:06,920
this is a video of these two-headed critters

1373
01:15:06,920 --> 01:15:08,600
doing their thing.

1374
01:15:08,600 --> 01:15:10,640
Okay, and so what we're doing now

1375
01:15:10,640 --> 01:15:15,640
is lots of computational modeling,

1376
01:15:16,680 --> 01:15:18,800
and actually using lots of ideas

1377
01:15:18,800 --> 01:15:21,960
from connectionist machine learning

1378
01:15:21,960 --> 01:15:23,480
to try and understand specifically

1379
01:15:23,480 --> 01:15:25,880
how the electrical circuits that are in these planaria

1380
01:15:25,880 --> 01:15:30,040
can store different types of target patterns

1381
01:15:30,040 --> 01:15:31,520
and reconstruct those patterns

1382
01:15:31,520 --> 01:15:34,080
even when the information has been damaged.

1383
01:15:34,080 --> 01:15:39,080
Now, I've shown you this story about two heads and so on.

1384
01:15:39,160 --> 01:15:41,440
It's not just about the number of heads.

1385
01:15:41,440 --> 01:15:43,240
One other amazing thing you can do

1386
01:15:43,240 --> 01:15:47,920
is push them to make heads of different species.

1387
01:15:47,920 --> 01:15:50,520
So here is a planarian with a nice triangular head

1388
01:15:50,520 --> 01:15:52,720
that's appropriate to his species.

1389
01:15:52,720 --> 01:15:53,920
We can cut off that head,

1390
01:15:53,960 --> 01:15:56,120
perturb the electrical network topology,

1391
01:15:56,120 --> 01:15:57,440
let them settle back down.

1392
01:15:57,440 --> 01:15:59,440
And when they regenerate their heads,

1393
01:15:59,440 --> 01:16:00,760
sometimes they make the normal head,

1394
01:16:00,760 --> 01:16:02,200
but sometimes they make round heads

1395
01:16:02,200 --> 01:16:03,640
like this S-Mediterranean.

1396
01:16:03,640 --> 01:16:06,560
Sometimes they make flat heads like this Pifelina.

1397
01:16:06,560 --> 01:16:07,800
Again, no genetic change here.

1398
01:16:07,800 --> 01:16:09,880
This has nothing to do with rewiring the hardware.

1399
01:16:09,880 --> 01:16:12,200
What it is is pushing that same machine

1400
01:16:12,200 --> 01:16:15,440
into other attractors in that enormous space

1401
01:16:15,440 --> 01:16:18,280
of morphogenetic configurations

1402
01:16:18,280 --> 01:16:19,680
that they're able to traverse.

1403
01:16:19,680 --> 01:16:20,840
They're normally very good

1404
01:16:20,840 --> 01:16:22,760
at going exactly where they need to go,

1405
01:16:22,760 --> 01:16:25,920
but they can in fact visit other regions of that state space

1406
01:16:25,920 --> 01:16:27,720
that normally belong to other species.

1407
01:16:27,720 --> 01:16:28,640
And not just the head shape,

1408
01:16:28,640 --> 01:16:31,640
but also the shape of the brain,

1409
01:16:31,640 --> 01:16:33,080
the distribution of stem cells,

1410
01:16:33,080 --> 01:16:34,440
just like these other species,

1411
01:16:34,440 --> 01:16:38,000
150 to 100 million years distance.

1412
01:16:38,000 --> 01:16:41,200
So again, this notion of reprogrammable biological hardware,

1413
01:16:41,200 --> 01:16:43,440
they can do other things beyond the default

1414
01:16:43,440 --> 01:16:44,800
that they normally do.

1415
01:16:44,800 --> 01:16:46,960
And by the way, they can go even further

1416
01:16:46,960 --> 01:16:50,560
into the latent morphospace of a typical planarian

1417
01:16:50,560 --> 01:16:53,360
and Darcy Thompson as early as 1917,

1418
01:16:53,360 --> 01:16:55,960
he had this notion of living beings

1419
01:16:55,960 --> 01:17:00,240
exploring various kinds of mathematical morphospace.

1420
01:17:00,240 --> 01:17:02,800
You can make them go further than a typical planarian

1421
01:17:02,800 --> 01:17:05,720
and you can make these things that are sort of,

1422
01:17:05,720 --> 01:17:06,840
they're not flat anymore.

1423
01:17:06,840 --> 01:17:08,360
They're round and cylindrical

1424
01:17:08,360 --> 01:17:09,480
and they're sort of hybrid shapes

1425
01:17:09,480 --> 01:17:11,720
or these crazy spiky things.

1426
01:17:11,720 --> 01:17:13,840
These wild type cells are capable

1427
01:17:13,840 --> 01:17:15,840
of building lots of different stuff.

1428
01:17:15,840 --> 01:17:19,200
And so what we're doing now is really trying

1429
01:17:19,200 --> 01:17:21,400
to make these full stack computational models

1430
01:17:21,400 --> 01:17:24,360
that go all the way from the lowest level molecular details

1431
01:17:24,360 --> 01:17:27,200
of which genes are turned on and off.

1432
01:17:27,200 --> 01:17:32,200
And then build the models of the bioelectric states,

1433
01:17:34,000 --> 01:17:37,560
the cellular and tissue-wide bioelectric states

1434
01:17:37,560 --> 01:17:39,080
that result from these ion channels

1435
01:17:39,080 --> 01:17:44,080
and eventually all the way up to body-wide decisions

1436
01:17:44,400 --> 01:17:46,120
and algorithms, which is what you need

1437
01:17:46,120 --> 01:17:47,520
for that anatomical compiler

1438
01:17:47,520 --> 01:17:48,920
that I talked about at the beginning,

1439
01:17:48,960 --> 01:17:50,320
which is to understand how the tissue

1440
01:17:50,320 --> 01:17:51,680
is actually making decisions

1441
01:17:51,680 --> 01:17:53,800
about large scale shape, number of heads,

1442
01:17:53,800 --> 01:17:55,560
type of heads and so on.

1443
01:17:55,560 --> 01:17:57,880
Okay, so just a couple more minutes

1444
01:17:57,880 --> 01:17:59,040
