and my goal becomes our goal.

1960
01:40:37,000 --> 01:40:41,040
And so by when a single cell in this diagram,

1961
01:40:41,040 --> 01:40:44,240
when a single cell has some size of a cognitive light going

1962
01:40:44,240 --> 01:40:46,800
and some ability to anticipate and remember,

1963
01:40:46,800 --> 01:40:51,800
a network of these cells has a bigger computational capacity

1964
01:40:52,320 --> 01:40:54,840
and a bigger spatial sensorium.

1965
01:40:54,840 --> 01:40:57,440
And it can actually have larger scale,

1966
01:40:57,440 --> 01:41:00,360
more complex states as set points.

1967
01:41:00,360 --> 01:41:02,320
And now you can start to see how a collection of cells

1968
01:41:02,320 --> 01:41:04,320
could actually work on something like building an arm

1969
01:41:04,320 --> 01:41:06,000
or building a whole body.

1970
01:41:06,000 --> 01:41:07,240
And so we can imagine,

1971
01:41:07,240 --> 01:41:08,360
and so we're doing this now

1972
01:41:08,360 --> 01:41:12,240
is doing these very specific computational models

1973
01:41:12,240 --> 01:41:15,760
of how little tiny homeostatic loops like this,

1974
01:41:15,760 --> 01:41:19,160
for example, measure the pH and act

1975
01:41:19,160 --> 01:41:21,920
become very large homeostatic loops

1976
01:41:21,920 --> 01:41:23,280
about something completely different.

1977
01:41:23,280 --> 01:41:25,960
Single cells cannot remember anything like this,

1978
01:41:25,960 --> 01:41:28,840
but a giant collection of cells could.

1979
01:41:28,840 --> 01:41:30,720
And so this is a very active area of research

1980
01:41:30,720 --> 01:41:33,760
is to figure out exactly how that scales up.

1981
01:41:33,760 --> 01:41:36,760
The implications are these,

1982
01:41:36,760 --> 01:41:38,240
here's what evolution has done.

1983
01:41:38,240 --> 01:41:41,200
Evolution has enabled single cells to work together

1984
01:41:41,200 --> 01:41:43,320
to enlarge their cognitive light cones

1985
01:41:43,320 --> 01:41:47,240
where the goals scale from the very humble goals

1986
01:41:47,280 --> 01:41:51,040
of single cells to the more grandiose goals of collectives

1987
01:41:51,040 --> 01:41:52,960
where they can work on something gigantic

1988
01:41:52,960 --> 01:41:54,640
like making sure you have four fingers.

1989
01:41:54,640 --> 01:41:56,560
This cell doesn't know anything about what a finger is,

1990
01:41:56,560 --> 01:41:58,440
but this collective does.

1991
01:41:58,440 --> 01:42:00,080
So evolution gave us the scale up,

1992
01:42:00,080 --> 01:42:01,800
but there's a failure mode to this.

1993
01:42:01,800 --> 01:42:03,200
The failure mode is cancer.

1994
01:42:03,200 --> 01:42:06,520
So here's where when these cells

1995
01:42:06,520 --> 01:42:08,880
are electrically isolated from each other,

1996
01:42:08,880 --> 01:42:12,080
this is human glioblastoma in culture.

1997
01:42:12,080 --> 01:42:14,000
So these individual cells can roll back

1998
01:42:14,000 --> 01:42:16,760
to their unicellular past.

1999
01:42:16,760 --> 01:42:18,360
They do not become more selfish.

2000
01:42:18,360 --> 01:42:20,800
A lot of game theory kind of approaches

2001
01:42:20,800 --> 01:42:22,800
treat cancer cells as more selfish.

2002
01:42:22,800 --> 01:42:24,120
They don't become more selfish.

2003
01:42:24,120 --> 01:42:25,760
Their cells get smaller.

2004
01:42:25,760 --> 01:42:26,600
They're just a selfish.

2005
01:42:26,600 --> 01:42:28,440
It's just that the self here is huge.

2006
01:42:28,440 --> 01:42:32,040
Their self is very tiny and they do the best they can.

2007
01:42:32,040 --> 01:42:36,360
But biometically, if you have that kind of weird perspective

2008
01:42:36,360 --> 01:42:39,920
on cancer as a disorder of selfhood,

2009
01:42:39,920 --> 01:42:42,320
then what you can do is something interesting.

2010
01:42:42,320 --> 01:42:44,720
And we did this years ago.

2011
01:42:45,720 --> 01:42:48,880
You can induce tumors using human oncogenes,

2012
01:42:48,880 --> 01:42:50,720
but what you can do is use these ion channels

2013
01:42:50,720 --> 01:42:53,440
to force the cells to be in the correct electrical state

2014
01:42:53,440 --> 01:42:55,520
to maintain proper communication.

2015
01:42:55,520 --> 01:42:57,920
And when you do that, even though the oncogene is blazingly

2016
01:42:57,920 --> 01:42:59,200
expressed, it's labeled in red here.

2017
01:42:59,200 --> 01:43:00,760
You can see it's all over the place.

2018
01:43:00,760 --> 01:43:01,440
There's no tumor.

2019
01:43:01,440 --> 01:43:02,640
This is the same animal.

2020
01:43:02,640 --> 01:43:06,280
There's no tumor because the genetics might have a defect.

2021
01:43:06,280 --> 01:43:08,080
The hardware might be a little bit broken.

2022
01:43:08,080 --> 01:43:10,520
But as long as the cell is physiologically

2023
01:43:10,520 --> 01:43:13,520
part of this network that contains large scale

2024
01:43:13,520 --> 01:43:16,720
goals like building nice skin, nice muscle, and so on,

2025
01:43:16,720 --> 01:43:18,760
they're kept away from tumorogenesis

2026
01:43:18,760 --> 01:43:22,880
and harness towards these large scale anatomical goals.

2027
01:43:22,880 --> 01:43:27,800
So the last piece I want to show you, it goes beyond this.

2028
01:43:27,800 --> 01:43:30,640
So we've been talking about goals in different spaces.

2029
01:43:30,640 --> 01:43:33,760
So the tiny metabolic goals of single cells,

2030
01:43:33,760 --> 01:43:37,560
the morphogenetic goals of cellular collectives.

2031
01:43:37,560 --> 01:43:40,680
And now we can ask the following question.

2032
01:43:40,680 --> 01:43:42,360
Where do these goals come from?

2033
01:43:42,360 --> 01:43:45,760
And what other goals can novel beings have?

2034
01:43:45,760 --> 01:43:47,480
And so this is a project that I also

2035
01:43:47,480 --> 01:43:51,040
have to do a disclosure here because Josh Bongard and I

2036
01:43:51,040 --> 01:43:53,200
have another company called Fauna Systems, which is all

2037
01:43:53,200 --> 01:43:56,520
about AI-designed biorebotics.

2038
01:43:56,520 --> 01:43:59,280
And this is all work done in collaboration

2039
01:43:59,280 --> 01:44:02,680
with a Bongard lab at this Institute of Computationally

2040
01:44:02,680 --> 01:44:04,520
Designed Organisms.

2041
01:44:04,520 --> 01:44:08,120
We asked the following question, how much plasticity

2042
01:44:08,120 --> 01:44:09,000
do these cells have?

2043
01:44:09,000 --> 01:44:11,040
And when they're liberated from their normal boundary

2044
01:44:11,040 --> 01:44:14,040
conditions of the animal, what will they do?

2045
01:44:14,040 --> 01:44:15,920
How will they reboot multicellularity?

2046
01:44:15,920 --> 01:44:19,120
How will they navigate anatomical and behavioral spaces?

2047
01:44:19,120 --> 01:44:20,160
What can they do?

2048
01:44:20,160 --> 01:44:22,240
So here's the experiment.

2049
01:44:22,240 --> 01:44:24,720
And all the biology here was done by Douglas Blackest

2050
01:44:24,720 --> 01:44:26,280
and the staff scientists in the group.

2051
01:44:26,280 --> 01:44:28,520
What we did was we took an early frog embryo.

2052
01:44:28,520 --> 01:44:33,480
And at this stage, where they have about 1,000 cells or so,

2053
01:44:33,480 --> 01:44:39,000
we cut off these cells up here, which are the skin.

2054
01:44:39,000 --> 01:44:41,960
This is all faded to be skin cells.

2055
01:44:41,960 --> 01:44:45,920
And we dissociated them and we put them back

2056
01:44:45,920 --> 01:44:48,000
in this little depression here.

2057
01:44:48,000 --> 01:44:49,560
And so they're just skin.

2058
01:44:49,560 --> 01:44:50,080
There's no nerve.

2059
01:44:50,080 --> 01:44:51,800
There's no muscle, just skin.

2060
01:44:51,800 --> 01:44:53,600
And what could they have done?

2061
01:44:53,600 --> 01:44:54,680
Well, they could have died.

2062
01:44:54,680 --> 01:44:58,240
They could have spread out and gotten away from each other.

2063
01:44:58,240 --> 01:45:00,240
They could have formed a nice two-dimensional monolayer,

2064
01:45:00,240 --> 01:45:01,680
the way that cell culture does.

2065
01:45:01,680 --> 01:45:04,280
What they did instead was something quite different.

2066
01:45:04,280 --> 01:45:05,800
Oops.

2067
01:45:06,240 --> 01:45:09,200
What they did instead, after we put them

2068
01:45:09,200 --> 01:45:11,680
in this little depression, all these little skin cells,

2069
01:45:11,680 --> 01:45:16,120
they got together and they formed this round thing

2070
01:45:16,120 --> 01:45:17,960
we call a xenobot.

2071
01:45:17,960 --> 01:45:19,880
It's called a xenobot because Xenopus lavus

2072
01:45:19,880 --> 01:45:20,720
is the name of the frog.

2073
01:45:20,720 --> 01:45:23,520
And we think it's a biorebotics platform, so xenobot.

2074
01:45:23,520 --> 01:45:25,680
What they do is these little guys

2075
01:45:25,680 --> 01:45:30,200
achieve spontaneous motion by using their cilia.

2076
01:45:30,200 --> 01:45:32,280
So frog skin has little hairs, little,

2077
01:45:32,280 --> 01:45:33,720
motile hairs called cilia, which it

2078
01:45:33,760 --> 01:45:36,600
uses to distribute mucus down the side of the animal.

2079
01:45:36,600 --> 01:45:39,360
So instead, what they do is they use it to row against the water.

2080
01:45:39,360 --> 01:45:40,520
So they start to swim.

2081
01:45:40,520 --> 01:45:41,600
So they can go in circles.

2082
01:45:41,600 --> 01:45:46,320
They can patrol back and forth like this.

2083
01:45:46,320 --> 01:45:47,880
They can have these collective behaviors

2084
01:45:47,880 --> 01:45:49,240
where they can go on a long journey

2085
01:45:49,240 --> 01:45:50,760
or they can interact with each other

2086
01:45:50,760 --> 01:45:53,960
or they can sit there doing nothing.

2087
01:45:53,960 --> 01:45:55,880
They have all kinds of behaviors.

2088
01:45:55,880 --> 01:46:00,080
Here's one moving in a maze in water.

2089
01:46:00,080 --> 01:46:01,800
So you'll see what it does as it goes.

2090
01:46:01,840 --> 01:46:04,080
It takes the corner without bumping into anything.

2091
01:46:04,080 --> 01:46:06,680
And then at this point, it spontaneously decides to turn around

2092
01:46:06,680 --> 01:46:07,960
and go back where it came from.

2093
01:46:07,960 --> 01:46:09,000
We are not pacing it.

2094
01:46:09,000 --> 01:46:10,200
We are not controlling it.

2095
01:46:10,200 --> 01:46:12,280
There are no, there's no neurons here.

2096
01:46:12,280 --> 01:46:17,160
This is a piece of skin living its own, its new best life.

2097
01:46:17,160 --> 01:46:21,400
And you're watching some of its behaviors.

2098
01:46:21,400 --> 01:46:26,560
It has all kinds of active calcium signaling.

2099
01:46:26,560 --> 01:46:30,360
This is the same technology used to read out brain signaling.

2100
01:46:30,440 --> 01:46:32,800
We are currently in the process of trying to decode all this

2101
01:46:32,800 --> 01:46:34,720
to see what the cells are saying to each other.

2102
01:46:34,720 --> 01:46:36,720
What are these two, what if anything

2103
01:46:36,720 --> 01:46:38,920
are these two Xenobots saying to each other?

2104
01:46:38,920 --> 01:46:40,120
They can regenerate.

2105
01:46:40,120 --> 01:46:42,720
So if you cut them almost in half, they will seal up.

2106
01:46:42,720 --> 01:46:43,560
So look at this.

2107
01:46:43,560 --> 01:46:45,680
So here's like 180 degree hinge right there.

2108
01:46:45,680 --> 01:46:48,720
Look at the power it takes to fold itself back

2109
01:46:48,720 --> 01:46:51,040
into its new Xenobot shape.

2110
01:46:51,040 --> 01:46:53,640
And something else that's amazing is by modeling.

2111
01:46:53,640 --> 01:46:57,320
And so Josh Bongard and Sam Kriegman in his lab

2112
01:46:57,320 --> 01:46:58,960
did a bunch of computational modeling

2113
01:46:59,000 --> 01:47:01,520
in the simulator of these bots running around.

2114
01:47:01,520 --> 01:47:04,280
And they noticed a kind of unusual predicted behavior

2115
01:47:04,280 --> 01:47:07,240
that they tend to rearrange their environment

2116
01:47:07,240 --> 01:47:08,080
in this weird way.

2117
01:47:08,080 --> 01:47:10,560
So they went, so we went ahead and we built some of the ones.

2118
01:47:10,560 --> 01:47:13,400
Then again, Doug sculpted some of these things

2119
01:47:13,400 --> 01:47:15,320
in ways that the AI suggested.

2120
01:47:15,320 --> 01:47:17,800
And we discovered something remarkable,

2121
01:47:17,800 --> 01:47:19,960
which is called kinematic replication.

2122
01:47:21,360 --> 01:47:24,480
Notice that we've made it impossible for these animals

2123
01:47:24,480 --> 01:47:26,760
to reproduce in the normal froggy fashion.

2124
01:47:26,760 --> 01:47:27,920
They don't have any other things there.

2125
01:47:27,920 --> 01:47:29,080
They're just skin.

2126
01:47:29,080 --> 01:47:31,880
But within a couple of days,

2127
01:47:31,880 --> 01:47:35,920
they discover a novel way of making copies of themselves

2128
01:47:35,920 --> 01:47:37,560
that's basically Von Neumann's dream.

2129
01:47:37,560 --> 01:47:40,480
It's able to construct copies of itself

2130
01:47:40,480 --> 01:47:42,680
from material it finds in the environment.

2131
01:47:42,680 --> 01:47:45,680
So this white stuff here, these are all loose skin cells

2132
01:47:45,680 --> 01:47:47,800
that we sprinkled into their world.

2133
01:47:47,800 --> 01:47:49,120
What they do is they run around

2134
01:47:49,120 --> 01:47:52,240
and they both collectively and individually,

2135
01:47:52,240 --> 01:47:54,480
they collect them into little balls

2136
01:47:54,480 --> 01:47:56,440
and then they sort of polish these little balls

2137
01:47:56,440 --> 01:47:57,800
and compact them.

2138
01:47:57,800 --> 01:48:00,840
And because they're not working with a passive,

2139
01:48:00,840 --> 01:48:02,560
some kind of passive particle,

2140
01:48:02,560 --> 01:48:04,920
they're working with an agential material,

2141
01:48:04,920 --> 01:48:07,160
just like we were the engineers,

2142
01:48:07,160 --> 01:48:09,400
Doug Blackison was working with an agential material,

2143
01:48:09,400 --> 01:48:10,880
these cells that have an agenda,

2144
01:48:10,880 --> 01:48:13,160
they like to assemble into the xenobot.

2145
01:48:13,160 --> 01:48:17,200
These little blobs become the next generation of xenobots.

2146
01:48:17,200 --> 01:48:18,040
And guess what they do?

2147
01:48:18,040 --> 01:48:19,360
They run around and collect more cells

2148
01:48:19,360 --> 01:48:23,240
and they become the next generation of xenobots and so on.

2149
01:48:23,240 --> 01:48:26,640
And so this ability to make copies of itself

2150
01:48:26,640 --> 01:48:28,760
using kinematic replication is just one of them.

2151
01:48:28,760 --> 01:48:31,480
We're just scratching the surface here of what they can do.

2152
01:48:31,480 --> 01:48:34,040
There is much, much more coming.

2153
01:48:34,040 --> 01:48:39,040
And so this suggests an interesting set of questions.

2154
01:48:40,040 --> 01:48:45,040
What did the frog genome actually learn during evolution?

2155
01:48:45,200 --> 01:48:46,680
Well, it can make frogs, sure,

2156
01:48:46,680 --> 01:48:48,880
and this is the normal tadpole path,

2157
01:48:48,880 --> 01:48:49,920
but it turns out,

2158
01:48:49,920 --> 01:48:51,480
and something we would have never known

2159
01:48:51,480 --> 01:48:53,840
if we hadn't tried this experiment,

2160
01:48:53,840 --> 01:48:55,280
it actually can do other things.

2161
01:48:55,280 --> 01:48:57,400
It can make the exact same genome.

2162
01:48:57,400 --> 01:48:59,240
We didn't edit the genome here.

2163
01:48:59,240 --> 01:49:01,480
We didn't give them any weird new nanomaterials.

2164
01:49:02,560 --> 01:49:05,840
The same genome can have a different developmental path.

2165
01:49:05,840 --> 01:49:07,880
This is what an old xenobot looks like.

2166
01:49:07,880 --> 01:49:11,680
I mean, it has this weird structure

2167
01:49:11,680 --> 01:49:13,400
that who knows what it's changing into.

2168
01:49:13,400 --> 01:49:14,920
And then it has different behaviors

2169
01:49:14,920 --> 01:49:17,600
that's different from what tadpoles do.

2170
01:49:17,600 --> 01:49:19,360
So here's some interesting things about it.

2171
01:49:19,360 --> 01:49:22,400
First of all, for any other creature,

2172
01:49:22,400 --> 01:49:25,560
when you ask why does it look the way it looks?

2173
01:49:25,560 --> 01:49:28,360
Why does it have certain behaviors and properties?

2174
01:49:28,360 --> 01:49:30,160
The answer is always the same, well, evolution.

2175
01:49:30,160 --> 01:49:31,240
So selection, right?

2176
01:49:31,240 --> 01:49:36,240
So for eons, the system was shaped,

2177
01:49:38,320 --> 01:49:40,360
it was selected for specific behaviors,

2178
01:49:40,360 --> 01:49:42,320
everything else died out and there you go.

2179
01:49:42,320 --> 01:49:45,000
But here, you can't use that story here

2180
01:49:45,000 --> 01:49:46,720
because there's never been any xenobots.

2181
01:49:46,720 --> 01:49:49,280
There has never been any selection to be a good xenobot.

2182
01:49:49,280 --> 01:49:53,040
Where did these capacities come from?

2183
01:49:53,040 --> 01:49:56,760
Where did their ability to do kinematic self-replication,

2184
01:49:56,760 --> 01:49:57,600
which to our knowledge,

2185
01:49:57,600 --> 01:49:59,240
doesn't exist anywhere in the biosphere,

2186
01:49:59,240 --> 01:50:00,640
where did that come from?

2187
01:50:00,640 --> 01:50:04,040
Now, we don't know what their cognitive capacities are.

2188
01:50:04,040 --> 01:50:05,040
We're studying that right now.

2189
01:50:05,040 --> 01:50:05,880
What can they sense?

2190
01:50:05,880 --> 01:50:06,720
Do they have preferences?

2191
01:50:06,720 --> 01:50:07,920
How can they learn?

2192
01:50:07,920 --> 01:50:10,280
We don't know any of that yet.

2193
01:50:10,280 --> 01:50:12,200
But we do know that they have novel morphologies

2194
01:50:12,200 --> 01:50:14,440
and novel behaviors and so where does that come from?

2195
01:50:14,440 --> 01:50:16,920
So one way to think about this

2196
01:50:16,920 --> 01:50:20,880
and that same genome by being probed in this way

2197
01:50:20,880 --> 01:50:22,720
is showing us a bit of the latent space,

2198
01:50:22,720 --> 01:50:24,320
a bit of what they are capable of.

2199
01:50:24,320 --> 01:50:26,400
So this is kind of, you know, Jeremy Gay,

2200
01:50:26,400 --> 01:50:27,840
who's an amazing graphic designer

2201
01:50:27,840 --> 01:50:29,400
that does a lot of our artwork,

2202
01:50:29,400 --> 01:50:32,880
did this homage to the famous Hofstadter book,

2203
01:50:32,880 --> 01:50:33,920
Gerd Lescher Bach,

2204
01:50:34,840 --> 01:50:39,840
where he was pointing out that how you look at certain objects

2205
01:50:42,760 --> 01:50:44,800
reveals what you see and what they can do.

2206
01:50:44,800 --> 01:50:46,640
And so through that frog genome,

2207
01:50:46,680 --> 01:50:48,640
when you look through it in a particular way,

2208
01:50:48,640 --> 01:50:50,840
yes, you can see the tadpoles

2209
01:50:50,840 --> 01:50:52,000
and yes, you can see xenobots

2210
01:50:52,000 --> 01:50:53,880
and maybe you can see other things.

2211
01:50:53,880 --> 01:50:56,160
And so what we can say here

2212
01:50:56,160 --> 01:51:00,480
is that these kind of synthetic organisms

2213
01:51:00,480 --> 01:51:01,880
are really a tool.

2214
01:51:01,880 --> 01:51:04,120
They're almost like a periscope or a telescope

2215
01:51:04,120 --> 01:51:06,880
that lets you look into another space

2216
01:51:06,880 --> 01:51:09,760
that we normally don't see into the space of possibilities

2217
01:51:09,760 --> 01:51:11,720
or for example, anatomical structure.

